[Student "S"]
{NORTH has 14 points and opens her 4-card \C suit.

SOUTH must respond, and with two 4-card Majors bids them "up-the-line", saying 1\H.

NORTH now shows his 4-card \S suit, and SOUTH again must bid. Since SOUTH is pretty weak he just 
raises to 2\S, which NORTH happily passes.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:KQ7.KQJ3.AT6.QT8 653.T4.QJ952.A54 A94.A7.K83.KJ962 JT82.98652.74.73"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1NT pass 4NT pass 6NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "705dd01f7e79441d64c63f6219612aaf67d157e15f18ebdc9ba9f574b2e34b61"]
[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_bidding"]
[Student "S"]
{EAST has a maximum 17 point 1NT bid.

WEST, with 16 points, can't tell if there are enough points for slam. If EAST has 
17 points then a slam should be makeable, but if EAST has only 15 points then he 
should settle for game.

The 4NT raise solves the problem. It tells EAST to bid 6NT with 17 points, pass 
with 15 points, and use best judgment with 16. Here EAST bids the slam.}

